.com/covid-19-iran-closes-holy-shrines-death-toll-hits-853-1857365/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Friday prayers were also suspended in Iran.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/coronavirus-iran-cancels-friday-prayers-across-country-1.70152305|title=Coronavirus: Iran cancels Friday prayers across country|website=gulfnews.com|accessdate=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323221038/https://gulfnews.com/world/mena/coronavirus-iran-cancels-friday-prayers-across-country-1.70152305|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA [[Tabligh Akbar]] event in [[Delhi]], India contributed to a cluster of more than 900 cases nationwide, and as of 23 April, approximately 30% of the total COVID-19 cases in India are linked to the this event.<ref name=livemint>{{cite news |url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/30-covid-19-cases-in-india-linked-to-tablighi-jamaat-event-govt-11587218560611.html|title=30% covid-19 cases in India linked to Tablighi Jamaat event: Govt\n|website=Live Mint|date=18 April 2020|accessdate=23 April 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200423091926/http://www.livemint.com/news/india/30-covid-19-cases-in-india-linked-to-tablighi-jamaat-event-govt-11587218560611.html|archivedate=23 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=ndtv>{{cite news |title=647 COVID-19 Cases In Last 2 Days Linked To Islamic Sect Meet In Delhi |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/647-coronavirus-cases-found-in-last-two-days-linked-to-islamic-sect-gathering-in-delhi-says-governme-2205635 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=NDTV|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403142140/https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/647-coronavirus-cases-found-in-last-two-days-linked-to-islamic-sect-gathering-in-delhi-says-governme-2205635|archivedate=3 April 2020}}</ref> There are several reports of Tablighi members not cooperating with authorities, misbehaving with medical personnels, hiding their travel history and went into hiding, with police authorities in some states had announced set up bounties for information regarding the attendees.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/covid-19-kanpur-police-announce-rs-10000-reward-for-info-on-tablighi-jamaat-members/articleshow/75252365.cms?from=mdr|title=COVID-19: Kanpur police announce Rs 10,000 reward for info on Tablighi Jamaat members|website=The Economic Times|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tablighi-jamaat-members-hiding-travel-history-could-incur-murder-charges-in-chhattisgarh-1665774-2020-04-11|title=Tablighi Jamaat members hiding travel history could incur murder charges in Chhattisgarh|website=India Today|date=11 April 2020|accessdate=23 April 2020|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200414014729/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tablighi-jamaat-members-hiding-travel-history-could-incur-murder-charges-in-chhattisgarh-1665774-2020-04-11|archivedate=14 April 2020}}</ref> This incident also led to a rise in [[Islamophobia|Islamophobic]] and [[Communalism (South Asia)|communal sentiments]] in India.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-52147260 |title=Coronavirus: Islamophobia concerns after India mosque outbreak |date= 3 April 2020 |work=BBC|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200404220948/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-52147260|archivedate=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/33017d73-d526-42ea-a2ee-b09078684534 |title=Muslims fear backlash of India's coronavirus fury |work=Financial Times |date=3 March 2020 |author1=Amy Kazmin |author2=Edward White |author3=Stefania Palma |access-date=3 April 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403112048/https://www.ft.com/content/33017d73-d526-42ea-a2ee-b09078684534 |archive-date=3 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> A large number of cases in [[Southeast Asia]] were tied to an another large [[Tabligh Akbar]] religious event held in late February 2020.<ref name=\"ANC wonder how dangerous\"/> On 19 March 2020, twenty-five thousand people gathered in [[Bangladesh]] to listen to \"healing verses\" from the [[Holy Qur'an]] \"to rid the country of the deadly virus.\"<ref name=\"Ng2020\">{{cite news |last1=Ng |first1=Kate |title=Massive prayer gathering is held to read 'healing verses' against coronavirus in Bangladesh |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/coronavirus-pandemic-bangladesh-india-muslim-prayer-gathering-healing-verses-a9410476.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=English |date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321031836/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/coronavirus-pandemic-bangladesh-india-muslim-prayer-gathering-healing-verses-a9410476.html |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== Judaism ===\n{{see also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Israel#Religious restrictions}}\n[[File:Praying outside due to Synagogue closure.jpg|thumb|[[Orthodox Jews]] [[Jewish prayer|praying]] on their porches due to closure of Synagogues. April 2020 in [[Borough Park, Brooklyn]]]]\nAt the [[Western Wall]], thousands of Jews gathered to [[Jewish prayer|pray]] on 15 February for an end to the coronavirus pandemic and this was led by Chief Rabbi of [[Safed]] [[Shmuel Eliyahu]].<ref name=\"Sheva2020\"/> By 12 March, when following a police request Israel's chief rabbis [[David Lau]] and [[Yitzhak Yosef]] instructed observant Jews to avoid visiting the holy site, few people continued praying there.<ref>{{cite web|last=Peltz |first=Jennifer |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/chief-rabbis-call-off-large-prayer-gatherings-at-western-wall/ |title=Israel's chief rabbis call on Jews to avoid visiting the Western Wall |publisher=The Times of Israel |date=2020-03-12 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> However, even when the government prohibited collective prayings with a [[minyan]] (publi\u0441 prayer quorum of 10 people or more) on 30 March, a special exemption was provided so that prayers could continue at the Western Wall three times a day.<ref>{{cite web|last=Winer |first=Stuart |url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/liveblog_entry/cabinet-said-to-approve-exemption-for-group-prayer-at-western-wall/ |title=Cabinet said to approve exemption for group prayer at Western Wall |publisher=The Times of Israel |date=2020-03-30 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nMany gatherings related to the Jewish celebration of [[Purim]] were canceled due to the COVID-19 pandemic.<ref name=\"Bailey 2020\"/>\n\nThe [[Rabbinical Council of America]], speaking on behalf of Orthodox Judaism, issued a guideline stating that \"public gatherings in synagogues and schools should be severely limited\".<ref name=\"Burke2020\"/> The [[Rabbinical Assembly]], speaking for Conservative Judaism, stated that \"Protecting human life overrides almost every other Jewish value\" and recommended that weddings be postponed.<ref name=\"Burke2020\"/>\n\nChief Rabbi [[Warren Goldstein]] suspends South Africa Synagogues.<ref>{{cite news |title=South Africa's shuls close to stop spread of coronavirus |url=https://www.sajr.co.za/news-and-articles/2020/03/19/south-africa-s-shuls-close-to-stop-spread-of-coronavirus |work=South Africa Jewish Report |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Ephraim Mirvis|chief rabbi]] in the United Kingdom advised the suspension of Jewish worship in synagogues.<ref name=\"Sherwood2020a\">{{cite web |last1=Sherwood |first1=Harriet |title=Church of England suspends all services over coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/17/church-of-england-suspends-services-coronavirus |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=English |date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Hinduism ===\n[[File:20200402 - The Times of India - COVID-19 lockdown - Ram Temple in Bhubaneswar wears a deserted look on Ram Navami.webm|thumb|thumbtime=0:28|On the occasion of [[Ram Navami]], Temple [[Ram Mandir, Bhubaneswar|Ram Mandir]] in the heart of Bhubaneswar is seen deserted.]]\n\nThe festival of [[Panguni Uthiram]], which is usually associated with processions, was canceled due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Hindu chariot and foot procession here cancelled |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/coronavirus-hindu-chariot-and-foot-procession-here-cancelled |publisher=[[The Straits Times]] |accessdate=17 March 2020 |language=English |date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316125038/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/coronavirus-hindu-chariot-and-foot-procession-here-cancelled |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Nepal government has given permission to only 25 pilgrims at once in the holy [[Pashupatinath Temple]] in Kathmandu,Nepal.<ref name=\"Sherwood2020\">{{cite web |last1=Sherwood |first1=Harriet |title=Religious festivals cancelled or scaled back due to coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/14/religious-festivals-cancelled-or-scaled-back-due-to-coronavirus |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=17 March 2020 |language=English |date=14 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316203319/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/14/religious-festivals-cancelled-or-scaled-back-due-to-coronavirus |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 9 March, thousands of devotees participated in [[Attukal pongala]], a festival where offerings are made to a Hindu goddess, despite the 'high alert' issued by the state government in India.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Kerala govt goes ahead with Attukal Pongala despite 5 new cases in state |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/kerala-govt-goes-ahead-with-attukal-pongala-despite-fear-of-coronavirus-outbreak-1653701-2020-03-08 |accessdate=29 March 2020 |work=India Today |agency=India Today |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309185604/https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/kerala-govt-goes-ahead-with-attukal-pongala-despite-fear-of-coronavirus-outbreak-1653701-2020-03-08 |archive-date=9 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Rajwi |first1=Tiki |title=Thousands of women flock to Thiruvananthapuram for Attukal Pongala today |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Thiruvananthapuram/thousands-of-women-flock-to-thiruvananthapuram-for-attukal-pongala-today/article31020975.ece |accessdate=29 March 2020 |work=The Hindu |date=9 March 2020 |language=en-IN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329152631/https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Thiruvananthapuram/thousands-of-women-flock-to-thiruvananthapuram-for-attukal-pongala-today/article31020975.ece |archive-date=29 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, the journey to [[Vaishno Devi Mandir]] in the Indian union territory of [[Jammu and Kashmir (union territory)|Jammu and Kashmir]] has been called off. Apart from this, the operation of all interstate buses coming to from Jammu and Kashmir has also been stopped. Shri Mata Vaishno Devi Shrine Board (SMVDSB), issued a consultation for foreigners not to visit the temple until 28 days after their arrival in India. Common people will not be able to go to the world famous Aarti to be held at the Ganges Ghat in Kashi. The district administration has banned entry of common people in Ganga Aarti. The organizers have also been asked to complete the Ganga Aarti in a simple way.\n\nAmidst a surge in confirmed cases across the state of [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Maharashtra|Maharashtra]] in [[India]], the health officials declared that several tourist and religious sites will be closed down as a precautionary measure. These sites included Siddhivinayak Temple in Mumbai, Tulja Bhavani Temple in Osmanabad district, Ajanta and Ellora Caves in Aurangabad district, Dagadusheth Halwai Ganapati Temple in Pune, Mumba Devi Temple in Mumbai and Saibaba Temple in Shirdi.\n\nThe [[Hindu festival]] of [[Holi]] was celebrated with caution before governments started enforcing lockdowns<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/holi-festival-2020/index.html |title=Holi 2020 celebrated with face masks and color explosions amid coronavirus fears &#124; CNN Travel |publisher=Cnn.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref> Other Hindu festivals such as [[Navaratri]], [[Ram Navami]], [[Hanuman Jayanti]], and various regional Hindu [[Indian New Year's days|new year days]] such as [[Vaisakhi]], [[Nyepi]], [[Ugadi]], [[Gudi Padwa]], [[Bohag Bihu]], [[Vishu]], [[Pahela Baishakh]], [[Maithili New Year|Jude Sheetal]], [[Pana Sankranti]], [[Kashmiri Hindu festivals#Navreh|Navreh]], [[Cheti Chand]], [[Puthandu]], [[Sinhalese New Year|Aluth Avurudda]], [[Sajibu Nongma Panba]], [[Bwisagu]], and [[Mesha Sankranti]] have to all be celebrated at home by Hindus around the world due to the strict lockdown in India and elsewhere. Prayer services have been live-streamed for viewers to watch at home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cbs6albany.com/news/coronavirus/virus-lockdown-changes-how-hindus-celebrate-holy-period |title=Virus lockdown changes how Hindus celebrate holy period &#124; WRGB |publisher=Cbs6albany.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/tv/holi-gudi-padwa-navratras-coronavirus-pandemic-dampens-the-festive-spirit/story-W8LFZQcuHMvJJFUbkctbwK.html |title=Holi, Gudi Padwa, Navratras: Coronavirus pandemic dampens the festive spirit - tv |publisher=Hindustan Times |date= |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/mumbai/city-rings-in-gudi-padwa-cheti-chand-with-whimper/article31168512.ece |title=City rings in Gudi Padwa, Cheti Chand with whimper |publisher=The Hindu |date=2020-03-26 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 April, thousands of devotees assembled in temples in various parts of [[West Bengal]] on the occasion of [[Ram Navami]] ignoring social distancing norms prescribed by the government during the ongoing nationwide lockdown period.<ref>{{cite news |title=Devotees visit temples on Ram Navami in West Bengal defying coronavirus lockdown |url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/east-and-northeast/devotees-visit-temples-on-ram-navami-in-west-bengal-defying-coronavirus-lockdown-820496.html |accessdate=5 April 2020 |work=Deccan Herald |date=2 April 2020 |language=en-IN }}</ref>\n\n=== Jainism ===\n[[Mahavir Janma Kalyanak|Mahavir Jyanti,]] the major festival of [[Jainism|Jains]] associated with the birth of [[Lord Mahavira]] that falls on 6th April, 2020 is usually celebrated by taking out large [[Procession]] has been cancelled through out the country and the followers of the religion has been instructed to carry religious rituals at home by the religious leaders<ref>{{Cite news|last=India|first=Press Trust of|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/coronavirus-aurangabad-jain-community-cancels-mahavir-jayanti-120031401014_1.html|title=Coronavirus: Aurangabad Jain community cancels Mahavir Jayanti|date=2020-03-14|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-04}}</ref> \n\n=== Sikhism ===\nThe [[Sikh Coalition]] recommended the cancelling of services at [[gurdwara]]s.<ref name=\"Burke2020\"/> Additionally, many Sikh gurudwaras have suspended the [[Langar (Sikhism)|offering of free food to gurudwara visitors]] and decided to broadcast the reading of scriptures on live stream.<ref name=\"Langar\">{{cite web |title=Food catering at Sikh temples suspended to limit Covid-19 spread, scripture readings to be live-streamed |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/suspension-of-food-catering-at-sikh-gurdwaras-to-limit-covid-19-spread-scripture-readings |publisher=[[The Straits Times]] |accessdate=17 March 2020 |language=English |date=16 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316225039/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/suspension-of-food-catering-at-sikh-gurdwaras-to-limit-covid-19-spread-scripture-readings |archive-date=16 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The Central Sikh Gurdwara Board has recommended that elderly Sikhs stay at home, though it has permitted weddings that have been scheduled to proceed.<ref name=\"Langar\"/> The [[Nagar Kirtan]]s associated with the holiday of [[Vaisakhi]] in the spring have also been suspended or postponed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/14/religious-festivals-cancelled-or-scaled-back-due-to-coronavirus |title=Religious festivals cancelled or scaled back due to coronavirus |work=The Guardian |date=14 March 2020 |authors=Harriet Sherwood |access-date=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Sikh]] Center of New York prepared more than 30,000 home-cooked meals for Americans in self-isolation amid the novel coronavirus outbreak. The Sikh community was approached by [[Mayor of New York City|New York's Mayor]] office for food packages that were handed out to several distributing federal agencies in the area.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/trending-news/story/coronavirus-sikh-volunteers-prepare-over-30-000-meal-packets-for-americans-in-self-isolation-1659059-2020-03-24 |title=Coronavirus: Sikh volunteers prepare over 30,000 meal packets for Americans in self-isolation |work=India Today |date=24 March 2020 |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/world/2020/mar/24/covid-19-new-york-sikhs-prepare-over-30000-free-meal-packets-for-americans-in-self-isolation-2120894.html |title=COVID-19: New York Sikhs prepare over 30,000 free meal packets for Americans in self-isolation |work=The New Indian Express |date=24 March 2020 |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Shiromani Gurdwara Parbandhak Committee]] offered a helping hand to treat corona positive patients at its hospitals.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/sgpc-offers-to-treat-corona-patients-at-its-hospitals-60948 |title=SGPC offers to treat corona patients at its hospitals |work=The Tribune |date=25 March 2020 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/sgpc-offers-to-treat-corona-patients-at-its-hospitals/1779319 |title=SGPC offers to treat corona patients at its hospitals |work=Outlook |date=25 March 2020 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> [[Delhi Sikh Gurudwara Management Committee]] provided its rooms to hospital staff as they were facing harassment at the hands of landlords and neighbours.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://theprint.in/india/meals-for-needy-shelter-for-hospital-staff-delhi-gurdwaras-step-up-with-aid-for-thousands/393161 |title=Meals for needy, shelter for hospital staff \u2014 Delhi gurdwaras step up with aid for thousands |work=The Print |date=1 April 2020 |access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Buddhism ===\nThe Cultural Corps of Korean Buddhism, which allows visitors to experience monastic life in one hundred and thirty-seven temples, has suspended that program.<ref name=\"Kaur2020\">{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/06/world/religion-modify-traditions-coronavirus-trnd/index.html|title=How religious communities are modifying traditions to prevent coronavirus spread|last1=Kaur|first1=Harmeet|publisher=CNN|accessdate=17 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317031906/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/06/world/religion-modify-traditions-coronavirus-trnd/index.html|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Buddhist Churches of America]] have cancelled services for the spring [[Higan]] holiday and other events at many of their temples.<ref name=\"BCA2020\">{{cite web |last1=Umezu |first1=Kodo |title=Special Message from the Bishop |url=https://www.buddhistchurchesofamerica.org/ |publisher=[[Buddhist Churches of America]] |accessdate=18 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113124645/http://www.buddhistchurchesofamerica.org/ |archive-date=13 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThere is concern that the virus may be hard to control during the travel and gatherings around [[Vesak]].\n\n== Legal issues ==\nThe [[First Liberty Institute]], a non-profit legal firm based in the United States, has issued guidance for religious institutions related to the suspension of their work during the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"Parke2020\"/>\n\nWhile many religious organizations suspended in-person services, activities and events,<ref name=\"Dias2020\"/><ref name=\"Ellis2020\">{{cite web |last1=Ellis |first1=Sarah |title=Even in the Bible Belt, coronavirus is closing churches. Here's how they're adapting |url=https://www.thestate.com/news/coronavirus/article241307671.html |publisher=The State |accessdate=24 March 2020 |language=English |date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324161521/https://www.thestate.com/news/coronavirus/article241307671.html |archive-date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> some gatherings happened despite advice or regulations to not meet in large groups.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Roth |first1=Andrew |first3=Shaun |last3=Walker |last2=Phillips |first2=Dom |title=Churchgoers all over world ignore physical distancing advice |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/29/church-goers-around-the-world-ignore-social-distance-advice |accessdate=30 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=30 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329235940/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/29/church-goers-around-the-world-ignore-social-distance-advice |archive-date=29 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kentucky.com/news/coronavirus/article241366951.html|title=Kentucky church held service against governor's warning. Visitor now has coronavirus.|date=2020-03-20|access-date=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200325172133/https://www.kentucky.com/news/coronavirus/article241366951.html|archive-date=25 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/coronavirus/ny-coronavirus-megachurch-covid-20200323-4iwmfxnf7ffvpmmetuy5h3mjem-story.html|title=Megachurch hosts 1,825 worshipers despite coronavirus pandemic|date=2020-03-23|access-date=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324074955/https://www.nydailynews.com/coronavirus/ny-coronavirus-megachurch-covid-20200323-4iwmfxnf7ffvpmmetuy5h3mjem-story.html|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200323000155|title=S. Korea to take legal actions against churches violating coronavirus guidelines|date=2020-03-23|access-date=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324043515/http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200323000155|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Some governments exempted religious organizations from the requirements on the number people allowed to be present at in-person gatherings during the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic.<ref name=\"Warikoo2020\">{{cite web |last1=Warikoo |first1=Niraj |title=Whitmer exempts Michigan churches from penalties for 50+ gatherings |url=https://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/2020/03/21/coronavirus-whitmer-updates-order-assemblies-exempt-churches-penalty/2885395001/ |publisher=[[Detroit Free Press]] |accessdate=24 March 2020 |language=English |date=21 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323190251/https://www.freep.com/story/news/local/michigan/2020/03/21/coronavirus-whitmer-updates-order-assemblies-exempt-churches-penalty/2885395001/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Research ==\nOn 8 March 2020 Italian scholars of law and religion at the Association of Academics of the Legal Regulation of the Religious Phenomenon started a research project, coordinated by Professo Pierluigi Consorti of the [[University of Pisa]]. They set up a website for collecting documents and brief comments about religion, law and the Covid-19 emergency.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Religion|Medicine}}\n*[[List of events affected by the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on education]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on politics]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on cinema]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on aviation]]\n*[[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on science and technology]]\n*[[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.unenvironment.org/faith-frontline-covid19 United Nations Interfaith Response to COVID-19]\n*[https://www.foxnews.com/us/coronavirus-update-church-sunday-service-online Churches cancel Sunday service, move online amid coronavirus outbreak - Fox News]\n*[https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2020/03/12/power-prayer-deal-reduce-coronavirus-anxiety-covid-19-column/5014472002/ The power of prayer to deal with coronavirus anxiety - USA Today]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/15/us/churches-coronavirus-services.html A Sunday Without Church: In Crisis, a Nation Asks, 'What is Community?' - The New York Times]\n*[https://elca.org/publichealth COVID-19/Coronavirus Resources - Evangelical Lutheran Church in America (ELCA)] \n*[https://thenalc.org/projects/pastoral-letter-on-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19/ Pastoral Letter on Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) - North American Lutheran Church (NALC)]\n*[https://www.washingtonpost.com/religion/2020/03/15/dc-churches-open-sunday-coronavirus-outbreak/ At D.C. churches that remained open Sunday, a mixture of defiance, encouragement and faith - The Washington Post]\n*[https://www.vox.com/2020/3/12/21172458/church-coronavirus-pandemic-communion-wine-common-cup-easter How churches are trying to