ls.rediff.com/movies/2008/nov/05sd1.htm B R Chopra's unforgettable movies] ''[[Rediff.com]]''\n\n{{B. R. Chopra}}\n{{Dadasaheb Phalke Award}}\n{{PadmaBhushanAwardRecipients 2000\u201309}}\n{{FilmfareAwardBestDirector}}\n{{FilmfareLifetimeAchievementAward}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chopra, Baldev Raj}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Indian male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Hindi-language film directors]]\n[[Category:People from Shaheed Bhagat Singh Nagar district]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:Dadasaheb Phalke Award recipients]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Bhushan in arts]]\n[[Category:University of the Punjab alumni]]\n[[Category:Hindi film producers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian film directors]]\n[[Category:Hindi screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:Film producers from Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male writers]]\n[[Category:Filmfare Awards winners]]\n", "name_user": "Vishalkrpathak", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baldev_Raj_Chopra"}
{"title_page": "Paul Finebaum", "text_new": "{{short description|American sports author, television and radio personality, and former columnist}}\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Paul Finebaum\n| image              = Paul Finebaum - June 2018.jpg\n| caption            = Finebaum in 2018\n| birthname          = Paul Finebaum\n| birth_place        = [[Memphis, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| birth_date         = \n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| alias              = \n| education          = [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[University of Tennessee]] 1978 (Political Science)\n| occupation         = [[Sports commentator|Sportscaster]], Sports author, TV / Radio personality, [[Sports columnist]]\n| years_active       = 1978\u2013present\n| agent              = \n| credits            = ''[[SportsCenter]]''<br />[[SEC Network]], [[Pardon My Take]], College football, ''The Paul Finebaum Radio Network''\n| salary             = \n| title              = \n| spouse             = Linda Hudson (m. 1990)\n| children           = \n| relatives          = \n| family             = Son of Benjamin Finebaum (father) Optometrist (died 1971) and Gloria Filderman Finebaum (mother)-former IRS Clerk. Pam Finebaum (Sister).\n}}\n'''Paul Finebaum''' is an American sports author, television and radio personality, and former columnist. His primary focus is sports, particularly those in the Southeast. After many years as a reporter, columnist, and sports-talk radio host in the Birmingham area, Finebaum was hired by [[ESPN]] in 2013 for its new [[SEC Network]] starting in 2014, and produces a radio show out of the network's regional base in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/9304935/paul-finebaum-joining-sec-network-espn|title=ESPN hires Paul Finebaum|date=May 23, 2013|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref>\n\nFinebaum attended [[Christian Brothers High School (Memphis, Tennessee)|Christian Brothers High School]] and [[White Station High School]] in Memphis before graduating from the [[University of Tennessee]], where he received a degree in Political Science, in 1978.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cci.utk.edu/smw-2014-paul-finebaum|title=SMW 2014 - Paul Finebaum|website=College of Communication & Information|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref> He served as host of the Paul Finebaum Radio Network, whose flagship station was on [[WJOX-FM]] from 2:05-6pm CST. The show was [[Radio syndication|syndicated]] in Alabama (27 stations), Mississippi (2 stations), Tennessee (3), and on single stations in Arkansas, Florida, Georgia, and South Carolina, and also heard on [[Sirius XM Radio]]'s Channel 81. His radio show is simulcast every day on the SEC Network and heard on Sirius XM radio. He is also a regular on ESPN's College Football Live, Sportscenter, Golic & Wingo, Get Up,  First Take, Outside the Lines, SEC Nation and College GameDay.\n\nESPN broadcaster [[Joe Tessitore]] said in a December 2018 podcast interview, \"If you asked me who are the two greatest interviewers on radio and television, I would say Paul Finebaum and [[Howard Stern]].\"<ref>{{cite magazine |host=Richard Deitsch|title=Sports Illustrated Media Podcast |magazine=Sports Illustrated |date=8 December 2016 |url=https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/play-episode/id997819235?i=1000420477984|access-date=3 November 2019}}</ref> In the College GameDay episode of Origins, James Andrew Miller said: \"Paul Finebaum knows the American Southeast like Jay-Z knows Brooklyn. And that's a big blast of wind at your back if your job is covering college football. His instincts as an interviewer rank him in the top tier of the sports world. And he is beyond mere savvy when it comes to speaking very virally.\"<ref>{{cite podcast |host=James Andrew Miller|title=Origins |website= |publisher= |date=10 January 2018 |url=https://podbay.fm/podcast/1266445999/e/1515604098|access-date=3 November 2019}}</ref> And in March 2019, Bobby Burack writing in [[The Big Lead]], praised his role as the preeminent voice in the game:  \"Finebaum's gives the most must-hear, mind-changing, make-you-stop-and-think opinions on the sport. Finebaum is one of ESPN's most valuable people.\" In September 2019, the [[New York Post]] ranked him No. 16 among the most influential people in college football, making him the highest-ranking on-air personality in a list dominated by conference commissioners and television moguls.{{Cn|date=November 2019}} In September 2016, the [[Wall Street Journal]] revealed that author [[Harper Lee]] was a daily listener of the Finebaum show.{{Cn|date=November 2019}}\n\nIn November, 2019, Bobby Burack of The Big Lead broke a major story saying that Finebaum had recently met in New York with his former ESPN president John Skipper, now the head of DAZN. And the executive chairman of the global streaming company was attempting to woo Finebaum to leave ESPN for megabucks. Some of have speculated in media circles it will be an important story to watch in early 2020, especially, with speculation about ESPN about to close a deal with the SEC to wrest away the valuable CBS Saturday package. John Talty of Al.com wrote Finebaum could be one of the biggest winners of the new deal, saying ``Already the face of ESPN'S SEC coverage, Finebaum becomes even more valuable to the network as it readies to invest hundreds of millions more into the conference ... With reports of Finebaum meeting with John Skipper, it comes even more imperative for ESPN brass to keep the SEC's dominant voice for when it official acquire the rights.'' \n\nMichael Smith of Sports Business Journal broke a story on Feb. 11, 2020 saying Finebaum was in talks with the four major television networks for the possible development of a sitcom on his show. It said the meetings included ABC Entertainment President Karey Burke. The SBJ report also indicated his agents at CAA are in talk with Hollywood about a Netflix documentary about his career. \n\nIn July 2018, after a much-publicized negotiation, Finebaum signed a new deal with ESPN. There had been speculation from The Sporting News in an article by Michael McCarthy Finebaum was being wooed by Fox Sports to possibly jump to the Big 10 Network. Dan Wolken of USA Today, in a July 10 article{{Cn|date=November 2019}} headlined: ``Paul Finebaum's potential departure is the biggest storyline in the SEC as media days nears.'' No terms of the deal were released, but John Ourand of the Sports Business Journal wrote new ESPN president Jimmy Pitaro \"personally had a hand in the negotiations with Finebaum and his reps at CAA (Nick Khan).'' Ourand said the new deal \"is believed to make Finebaum ESPN's second-highest-paid college football talent, behind only analyst Kirk Herbstreit.\" SBJ reported the new deal called for a salary of approximately $2 million annually.{{Cn|date=November 2019}}\n\nHe has been a guest on television's [[Larry King Live]], [[CBS]]' [[60 Minutes]], [[Nancy Grace]], [[MSNBC]]'s [[Morning Joe]], [[HBO]], and [[Tru TV]]. He is a recurring guest on [[Pardon My Take]]. On Jan. 8, the Alabama Sports Hall of Fame announced Finebaum will be the recipient of the 2020 Mel Allen Award and will be honored at the induction banquet on May 2. \n\n==News reporter==\nFinebaum arrived in Birmingham in 1980 and became a columnist and reporter for the ''[[Birmingham Post-Herald]].'' Finebaum's work has earned him more than 250 national, regional, and area sports writing awards, including his stories on the recruitment of [[Alabama Crimson Tide men's basketball|Alabama basketball]] player [[Buck Johnson]]. He also in 1993 broke the story of [[Antonio Langham]], a [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|University of Alabama]] football player who signed a contract with a [[sports agent]] while playing for the school, which led to a NCAA probation for the school. He was also the first to report the firing of [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn University]] coach [[Terry Bowden]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://finebaum.com/finebaumbio.html|title=Cumulus Media|publisher=finebaum.com|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref> Finebaum joined the ''Mobile Press Register'' in 2001 where he wrote a twice-weekly (later weekly) column with the column syndicated to other newspapers. Finebaum discontinued the column in December 2010.<ref>{{cite news|date=February 2, 2011|url=http://www.njeffersonnews.com/localsports/x2104923466/FINE-GONE-Paul-Finebaum-ends-sybdicated-column|title=FINE-GONE: Paul Finebaum ends syndicated column|last=Carter|first=Robert|newspaper=[[The North Jefferson News]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120905225926/http://www.njeffersonnews.com/localsports/x2104923466/FINE-GONE-Paul-Finebaum-ends-sybdicated-column|archivedate=September 5, 2012}}</ref> On September 1, Finebaum returned to writing with his first column for Sports Illustrated. His weekly column appears every Thursday at SI.com.\n\n==Radio career==\n===Early career===\nFinebaum started his radio appearances in the mid-1980s by giving morning commentary on the Mark and Brian Radio Show on [[WJOX-FM|WAPI-FM (I-95)]]. After starting his own afternoon radio show a few years later on [[WAPI-AM]], his program quickly became the highest-rated sport-talk show in Birmingham. In October 1993, Finebaum moved his [[Sports radio|sports-talk show]] to [[WERC (AM)|WERC]].\n\n===The Paul Finebaum Radio Network===\nIn 2001, Finebaum, along with Network Director Pat Smith and Producer Kerry Adams, launched ''The Paul Finebaum Radio Network,'' syndicated with affiliates across the southeast. It was named in 2004 by ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' as one of the top 12 sports radio shows in the United States. In January 2007, his radio show moved to [[WJOX-FM|WJOX]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.decaturdaily.com/decaturdaily/sports/070120/radio.shtml|title=Finebaum joins WJOX radio station|publisher=[[The Decatur Daily]] (via [[Associated Press]])|date=January 20, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20070521234552/http://www.decaturdaily.com/decaturdaily/sports/070120/radio.shtml|archivedate=May 21, 2007}}</ref>\n\nFinebaum found himself embroiled at the center of one of biggest college sports stories in America in 2011 \u2013 the poisoning of the famous trees on [[Auburn Tigers#Toomer's Corner|Toomer's Corner]] at [[Auburn University]]. The man charged, Harvey Updyke, called the Finebaum show, claiming to have poisoned the trees. The audio of the call was played on nearly every national radio show and television newscast in the nation. In the aftermath, Finebaum was featured on the ''[[NBC Nightly News|NBC Nightly News with Brian Williams]]'', appeared on CNN, ESPN, MSNBC, and several other networks. He also was blamed by many for the event including one caller saying \"if anything else happens, there will be blood on your hands.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2011/02/finebaum_catching_flak_blame_f.html|title=Is Finebaum to blame for Auburn tree poisoning? Will controversy help or hurt him?|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref> On April 21, Updyke appeared again on the Finebaum show, speaking publicly for the first time since the incident, breaking his long silence. The interview, perhaps the most listened to ever in the history of the Finebaum show, made national news, appearing in publications ranging from ''[[The New York Times]]'' to ESPN's ''[[SportsCenter]]''. Updyke ended the 45-minute interview with his signature ''Roll Damn Tide.''\n\n===ESPN===\nFinebaum's show went off the air on WJOX temporarily on January 21, 2013, when his contract with Cumulus and WJOX expired. The New Yorker reported he \"had talks with ESPN and CBS, about joining their national radio networks, and with SiriusXM, about moving permanently to satellite.\"<ref name=\"newyorker\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2012/12/10/121210fa_fact_wiedeman|magazine=[[The New Yorker]]|date=December 10, 2012|author=Wideman, Reeves|title=King of the South: How Paul Finebaum became Alabama\u2019s biggest booster}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, Finebaum signed with ESPN to appear on its new SEC Network beginning in 2014, and also host a daily radio show based out of Charlotte.<ref name=NYTimes>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/22/sports/ncaafootball/paul-finebaum-joins-espn.html|title=Radio Host Paul Finebaum joins ESPN|last=Bishop|first=Greg|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\nFinebaum's television contributions have been numerous. In Birmingham he currently{{When|date=November 2019}} appears as a sports analyst for [[WBRC]]. He was sports director for [[WIAT-TV]] from 1998 to 2002 and co-hosted individual shows on [[WVTM-TV]] and [[WBMA-LD|WBMA]].\n\nFinebaum also had a leading role in ESPN's documentary ''Roll Tide/War Eagle''. The producers used Finebaum and his program as the voice of the documentary, which debuted on November 8, 2011.\n\nAs part of the deal Finebaum signed with ESPN in May 2013, he agreed to appear on its new [[SEC Network]] starting in 2014, hosting ''The Paul Finebaum Show'' in simulcast for ESPN Radio.<ref name=NYTimes /> As an extension of the radio show, Finebaum has also hosted special broadcasts on SEC Network as part of [[ESPN Megacast]]s involving SEC teams\u2014the ''Finebaum Film Room''\u2014particularly during [[College Football Playoff National Championship]] games.<ref name=al-finebaumtrainwreck>{{cite web|title=Paul Finebaum hears 'train wreck' predictions for live Iron Bowl show, phones ready this time|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2014/11/paul_finebaum_iron_bowl_2014_live.html|website=AL.com|accessdate=30 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nFinebaum's books include his popular ''I Hate...'' series, including ''I Hate Michigan: 303 Reasons Why You Should, Too,'' and several dozen similarly titled works.\n\nFinebaum's other books include ''The Worst of Paul Finebaum'' ({{ISBN|1881548120}}), a 1994 compilation of some of the newspaper columns he has written; and ''Finebaum Said'' ({{ISBN|1931656037}}), a 2001 collection of columns and interviews.\n\nOn March 27, 2013, the Birmingham News reported that Finebaum agreed to an advance (later reported to be $650,000) with [[HarperCollins]] to write a book about the radio show. HarperCollins Senior Vice President and Executive Editor David Hirshey said \"We expect this book to occupy the same spot on the best-seller list that Alabama occupies in the BCS rankings \u2013 number one.\" In February, Publishers Weekly reported the book would arrive on August 5 with a first run of 150,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2013/03/paul_finebaum_agrees_to_book_d.html|title=Paul Finebaum agrees to book deal with HarperCollins for memoir about his radio show|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thestate.com/2013/10/05/3021379/paul-finebaum-can-talk-will-travel.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=October 13, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014172610/http://www.thestate.com/2013/10/05/3021379/paul-finebaum-can-talk-will-travel.html |archivedate=October 14, 2013 }}</ref> The book, which was excerpted in the ''Wall Street Journal'' on August 5, quickly made the ''New York Times'' best-seller list, landing at No. 6 among sports books. The book remained on the best-seller list for five months.\n\n==Recognition==\n[[File:Paul Finebaum Jan 2018 2.jpg|thumb|Finebaum (left) at the [[2018 College Football Playoff National Championship]] media day]]\nIn 2002, Finebaum was named by ''[[The Tennessean]]'' in Nashville as one of the [[Southeastern Conference]]'s Top Power Brokers. In July 2009, ''[[The Orlando Sentinel]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/college/orl-sportspowerbox10071009jul10,0,6725131.story|title=The SEC's 10 most powerful people|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref> named Finebaum as one of the SEC's 10 most powerful people. On January 11, 2011, [[CNBC]]'s Emmy-Award-winning sports reporter, [[Darren Rovell]] wrote: \"Back 2 back titles by Alabama & Auburn make Finebaum the most powerful small market sports media member in the nation\" and called him \"the best listener of any sports talk radio host.\" In December 2012, [[Sports Illustrated]], in its year-end review of sports media, listed gave Finebaum an Honorable Mention along with 10 other names for \"Best National Radio Voice\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/more/news/media-awards-2012/ | publisher=CNN | title=SI.com's Media Awards: Best, worst from 2012 | date=December 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Reeves Wiedeman]] profiled the radio host in a 5,000-word article, \"King of the South\", in the December 10, 2012 edition of ''[[the New Yorker]]''. According to the Wiedeman, it was The New Yorker's first major piece on a college football figure in more than 10 years.<ref name=\"newyorker\" /> Several months later, on February 6, 2013, The ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', in a profile by writer [[Rachel Bachman]], stated: \"Paul Finebaum is not only one of the nation's best-known sports-talk radio hosts. He is perhaps college football's best-known voice since TV announcer [[Keith Jackson]] retired.\" The Journal ended the story, referring to Finebaum as \"the [[Oprah Winfrey]] of college football.\" On March 6, 2013, ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''{{'}}s Richard Deitsch unveiled a ranking of the 20 Most Powerful People in Sports Media nationally and Finebaum came in at No. 17.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/more/news/20130306/most-powerful-people-sports-media/ | publisher=CNN | title=Ranking the 10 most powerful people in sports media | date=March 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, ''The Big Lead'', part of USA Today's sports online network, ranked Finebaum No. 18 in a piece on ''The 25 Most Powerful People in Sports Media'', writing: \"He was profiled by the New Yorker, and that was before he became a multimedia presence on ESPN and the SEC Network. His radio show is a focal point for college football fans and media members. He can alter the sport's national discussion with an interview, a hot bit of gossip, and offhand comment or a tweet.\" {{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nIn July 2015, the college football website, ''Saturday Down South'', ranked Finebaum No. 3 among the SEC's most influential people, saying \"Finebaum has masterfully positioned himself to be \"the voice of the SEC.\"{{Cn|date=November 2019}} At the conclusion of SEC Media Days, \"Saturday Down South\" also ranked the top 10 commentators and media figures, and Finebaum was ranked No. 1. \"There was really little question as to who would top this list,\" wrote Saturday Down South. \"In the midst of facilitating what can turn into a crazy sideshow, Finebaum has managed to develop one of the league's most respected voices.\"{{Cn|date=November 2019}}\n\nIn January 2017, The Big Lead had Finebaum No. 25 on a list of ''The 30 Most Powerful Talents in Sports Media Today'', saying: \"Finebaum owns the SEC region, and when he wields his cudgel on a coach or program in scandal, it cuts deeper than just about any voice. He has his finger on the pulse of Nick Saban and Alabama, which you might as well write in the CFB playoffs every year in a Sharpie.\" On February 1, 2018 Jason Barrett of Barrett Sports Media, polled 35 radio executives from the nation, and listed Finebaum No. 7 in \"America's Top 20 National Sports Shows of 2017.\"{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} In January 2019, The Big Lead ranked the 75 Most Powerful People in the Sports Media, a list ranging from Disney chairman Bob Iger and Fox chief Rupert Murdoch to LeBron James to sports talent on various network. Finebaum came in at No. 35, tied with Jay Bilas. ``Paul Finebaum and Jay Bilas are arguably the most influential voices on college football and college basketball respectively. Finebaum has a huge impact on the most important region in the sport ... They (Finebaum and Bilas) are two truly untouchable voices.\" In February 2019, Jason Barrett's annual ranking of the Top 20 National Sports Shows saw Finebaum land at No. 6. In July 2019, Buddy Martin, a respected journalist, and now editor of GatorBait Magazine, conducted a poll at SEC Media Days among media members and found Finebaum to be the most influential member of the SEC media, and it was nearly unanimous. ``Nobody else was even close,'' Martin wrote. Alan Blinder, who covers college football for the New York Times, voted three times. 1. Paul Finebaum, 2. Paul Finebaum and 3. Paul Finebaum. Mike Bianchi of the Orlando Sentinel was even stronger:``Paul Finebaum is not only the 'Most Influential' member here - he's the `Most Influential' in all of college football.''\n\nIn October 2013, the University of Tennessee presenting Finebaum with the \"Accomplished Alumni Award,\" \"which recognizes notable alumni for their success and distinction within their field.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utk.edu/tntoday/2013/10/18/renowned-sports-journalist-honored-accomplished-alumni-award|title=Renowned Sports Journalist Honored with Accomplished Alumni Award|date=October 18, 2013|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n\n'On June 23, 2016, Finebaum delivered the keynote at the annual meeting of the Associated Press Sports Editors annual convention in Charlotte. He gave an emotionally charged address, challenging the group to remain firm to its core principals, adding \"journalism is not a reality show.\" A copy of the speech is available at apsportseditors.org.[citation needed] In May 2018, Finebaum delivered the eulogy of his close friend SEC Commissioner Mike Slive in Birmingham, an occasion live-streamed on Al.com. Kevin Scarbinsky, the long-time columnist, said: His eulogy for dear friend Mike Slive had to be among the most personal and painful minutes Finebaum ever spent behind a microphone. Paul's moving tribute may have been his finest hour.[citation needed] Finebaum has also received enormous praise for his handling of the COVID-19 crisis, with stories such as Tony Barnhart in SI.com, saying \"Finebaum's daily show has served as a respite for fans whose sports and lives have shattered. USA Today's Dan Wolken has also heaped praise in a piece titled: \"College foobtball fans seek comfort in familiar voice, Paul Finebaum. And Bryan Curtis writing in The Ringer described the host in a story, titled: \"How Sports Radios Became America's Grief Counselors. Wrote Curtis: ``In normal times, the Paul Finebaum show is a college football food fight and diorama of Southern life. In the past three weeks, it has a evolved into a forum for coronaries fear, healing and occasional shaming. Curtis continued: ``Listening to the show is like prowling on Nextdoor. You hear fear expressed by regular people rather than fear repackaged by the Cuomo brothers ... Finebaum is already his audience's friend. As he did after the 2011 tornadoes, he wants to be its sounding board, its grief counselor.\n\nPersonal life{Cn|date=November 2019}}\n\n==Personal life==\nFinebaum was born in Memphis, Tennessee.  He and his wife Linda Hudson have been married since 1990.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.annistonstar.com/sports/once-a-birmingham-sports-columnist-finebaum-hits-the-big-time/article_b52c9876-4ec5-11e5-9d7c-1f7024629a1c.html|title=Once a Birmingham sports columnist, Finebaum hits the big time at ESPN|date=August 23, 2015|last=Hester|first=Wayne|newspaper=[[The Anniston Star]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006050950/http://www.annistonstar.com/sports/once-a-birmingham-sports-columnist-finebaum-hits-the-big-time/article_b52c9876-4ec5-11e5-9d7c-1f7024629a1c.html|archivedate=October 26, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Finebaum is [[Jewish]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url= http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2012/12/10/king-of-the-south|title= King of the South|date=December 10, 2012|last=Wiedman|first=Reeves|magazine=[[The New Yorker]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/espn/page2/story?id=1907341 |title=Rammer Jammer Yellow Hammer |last=St. John |first=Warren |date=December 10, 2012 |access-date=October 2, 2019 |publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/podcasts/hang_up_and_listen/2012/12/paul_finebaum_alabama_hang_up_and_listen_on_the_jovan_belcher_murder_suicide.html|title=Hang Up and Listen: The How To Talk About a Murder-Suicide Edition. Slate\u2019s sports podcast on Jovan Belcher, Alabama sports radio host Paul Finebaum, and the contretemps over the Spurs resting their starters.|date=December 3, 2012|last1=Fatsis|first1=Stefan|last2=Levin|first2=Josh|last3=Pesca|first3=Mike|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Barnes, Susan. (Summer 2005) \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20060507224422/http://pr.tennessee.edu/alumnus/alumarticle.asp?id=628 The Devil We Know]\". ''Tennessee Alumnus Magazine''. Vol. 85, No. 3 \u2013 accessed April 16, 2006\n* Paul Finebaum is \"the most influential sports-talk personality in the Southeast\" \u2013 Huntsville Times, August 21, 2003.\n* \"Paul Finebaum, the state's most influential sports columnist and talk-show host\" \u2013 New York Times, May 4, 2003.\n* Fowler, Jeremy. \"Finebaum voted as one of the SEC's 10 most powerful people\"- \"[http://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/college/orl-sportspowerbox10071009jul10,0,6725131.story ]\". Orlando Sentinel, July 10, 2009.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.facebook.com/PaulFinebaum Paul Finebaum Official Facebook Page]\n*[http://www.finebaum.com Paul Finebaum Radio Network official site]\n*[http://www.al.com/sports/birminghamnews/index.ssf?/base/sports/116921267611600.xml&coll=2 Finebaum headed to WJOX, ''Birmingham News'']\n*[http://www.cranehill.com/ihate.html Cranehill Press \"I Hate...\" Series]\n* [http://www.bhamwiki.com/wiki/index.php?title=Paul_Finebaum Paul Finebaum] article at BhamWiki.com\n*[http://www.radiojunkee.com Listen to Paul Finebaum Show on RadioJunkee.com]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Finebaum, Paul}}\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n[[Category:American sportswriters]]\n[[Category:American sports radio personalities]]\n[[Category:American television personalities]]\n[[Category:Writers from Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:People from Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Tennessee alumni]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Alabama]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Jewish American sportspeople]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American sports author, television and radio personality, and former columnist}}\n{{BLP sources|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Paul Finebaum\n| image              = Paul Finebaum - June 2018.jpg\n| caption            = Finebaum in 2018\n| birthname          = Paul Finebaum\n| birth_place        = [[Memphis, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| birth_date         = \n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| alias              = \n| education          = [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[University of Tennessee]] 1978 (Political Science)\n| occupation         = [[Sports commentator|Sportscaster]], Sports author, TV / Radio personality, [[Sports columnist]]\n| years_active       = 1978\u2013present\n| agent              = \n| credits            = ''[[SportsCenter]]''<br />[[SEC Network]], [[Pardon My Take]], College football, ''The Paul Finebaum Radio Network''\n| salary             = \n| title              = \n| spouse             = Linda Hudson (m. 1990)\n| children           = \n| relatives          = \n| family             = Son of Benjamin Finebaum (father) Optometrist (died 1971) and Gloria Filderman Finebaum (mother)-former IRS Clerk. Pam Finebaum (Sister).\n}}\n'''Paul Finebaum''' is an American sports author, television and radio personality, and former columnist. His primary focus is sports, particularly those in the Southeast. After many years as a reporter, columnist, and sports-talk radio host in the Birmingham area, Finebaum was hired by [[ESPN]] in 2013 for its new [[SEC Network]] starting in 2014, and produces a radio show out of the network's regional base in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/9304935/paul-finebaum-joining-sec-network-espn|title=ESPN hires Paul Finebaum|date=May 23, 2013|work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref>\n\nFinebaum attended [[Christian Brothers High School (Memphis, Tennessee)|Christian Brothers High School]] and [[White Station High School]] in Memphis before graduating from the [[University of Tennessee]], where he received a degree in Political Science, in 1978.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cci.utk.edu/smw-2014-paul-finebaum|title=SMW 2014 - Paul Finebaum|website=College of Communication & Information|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref> He served as host of the Paul Finebaum Radio Network, whose flagship station was on [[WJOX-FM]] from 2:05-6pm CST. The show was [[Radio syndication|syndicated]] in Alabama (27 stations), Mississippi (2 stations), Tennessee (3), and on single stations in Arkansas, Florida, Georgia, and South Carolina, and also heard on [[Sirius XM Radio]]'s Channel 81. His radio show is simulcast every day on the SEC Network and heard on Sirius XM radio. He is also a regular on ESPN's College Football Live, Sportscenter, Golic & Wingo, Get Up,  First Take, Outside the Lines, SEC Nation and College GameDay.\n\nESPN broadcaster [[Joe Tessitore]] said in a December 2018 podcast interview, \"If you asked me who are the two greatest interviewers on radio and television, I would say Paul Finebaum and [[Howard Stern]].\"<ref>{{cite magazine |host=Richard Deitsch|title=Sports Illustrated Media Podcast |magazine=Sports Illustrated |date=8 December 2016 |url=https://podcasts.apple.com/us/podcast/play-episode/id997819235?i=1000420477984|access-date=3 November 2019}}</ref> In the College GameDay episode of Origins, James Andrew Miller said: \"Paul Finebaum knows the American Southeast like Jay-Z knows Brooklyn. And that's a big blast of wind at your back if your job is covering college football. His instincts as an interviewer rank him in the top tier of the sports world. And he is beyond mere savvy when it comes to speaking very virally.\"<ref>{{cite podcast |host=James Andrew Miller|title=Origins |website= |publisher= |date=10 January 2018 |url=https://podbay.fm/podcast/1266445999/e/1515604098|access-date=3 November 2019}}</ref> And in March 2019, Bobby Burack writing in [[The Big Lead]], praised his role as the preeminent voice in the game:  \"Finebaum's gives the most must-hear, mind-changing, make-you-stop-and-think opinions on the sport. Finebaum is one of ESPN's most valuable people.\" In September 2019, the [[New York Post]] ranked him No. 16 among the most influential people in college football, making him the highest-ranking on-air personality in a list dominated by conference commissioners and television moguls.{{Cn|date=November 2019}} In September 2016, the [[Wall Street Journal]] revealed that author [[Harper Lee]] was a daily listener of the Finebaum show.{{Cn|date=November 2019}}\n\nIn November, 2019, Bobby Burack of The Big Lead broke a major story saying that Finebaum had recently met in New York with his former ESPN president John Skipper, now the head of DAZN. And the executive chairman of the global streaming company was attempting to woo Finebaum to leave ESPN for megabucks. Some of have speculated in media circles it will be an important story to watch in early 2020, especially, with speculation about ESPN about to close a deal with the SEC to wrest away the valuable CBS Saturday package. John Talty of Al.com wrote Finebaum could be one of the biggest winners of the new deal, saying ``Already the face of ESPN'S SEC coverage, Finebaum becomes even more valuable to the network as it readies to invest hundreds of millions more into the conference ... With reports of Finebaum meeting with John Skipper, it comes even more imperative for ESPN brass to keep the SEC's dominant voice for when it official acquire the rights.'' \n\nMichael Smith of Sports Business Journal broke a story on Feb. 11, 2020 saying Finebaum was in talks with the four major television networks for the possible development of a sitcom on his show. It said the meetings included ABC Entertainment President Karey Burke. The SBJ report also indicated his agents at CAA are in talk with Hollywood about a Netflix documentary about his career. \n\nIn July 2018, after a much-publicized negotiation, Finebaum signed a new deal with ESPN. There had been speculation from The Sporting News in an article by Michael McCarthy Finebaum was being wooed by Fox Sports to possibly jump to the Big 10 Network. Dan Wolken of USA Today, in a July 10 article{{Cn|date=November 2019}} headlined: ``Paul Finebaum's potential departure is the biggest storyline in the SEC as media days nears.'' No terms of the deal were released, but John Ourand of the Sports Business Journal wrote new ESPN president Jimmy Pitaro \"personally had a hand in the negotiations with Finebaum and his reps at CAA (Nick Khan).'' Ourand said the new deal \"is believed to make Finebaum ESPN's second-highest-paid college football talent, behind only analyst Kirk Herbstreit.\" SBJ reported the new deal called for a salary of approximately $2 million annually.{{Cn|date=November 2019}}\n\nHe has been a guest on television's [[Larry King Live]], [[CBS]]' [[60 Minutes]], [[Nancy Grace]], [[MSNBC]]'s [[Morning Joe]], [[HBO]], and [[Tru TV]]. He is a recurring guest on [[Pardon My Take]]. On Jan. 8, the Alabama Sports Hall of Fame announced Finebaum will be the recipient of the 2020 Mel Allen Award and will be honored at the induction banquet on May 2. \n\n==News reporter==\nFinebaum arrived in Birmingham in 1980 and became a columnist and reporter for the ''[[Birmingham Post-Herald]].'' Finebaum's work has earned him more than 250 national, regional, and area sports writing awards, including his stories on the recruitment of [[Alabama Crimson Tide men's basketball|Alabama basketball]] player [[Buck Johnson]]. He also in 1993 broke the story of [[Antonio Langham]], a [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|University of Alabama]] football player who signed a contract with a [[sports agent]] while playing for the school, which led to a NCAA probation for the school. He was also the first to report the firing of [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn University]] coach [[Terry Bowden]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://finebaum.com/finebaumbio.html|title=Cumulus Media|publisher=finebaum.com|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref> Finebaum joined the ''Mobile Press Register'' in 2001 where he wrote a twice-weekly (later weekly) column with the column syndicated to other newspapers. Finebaum discontinued the column in December 2010.<ref>{{cite news|date=February 2, 2011|url=http://www.njeffersonnews.com/localsports/x2104923466/FINE-GONE-Paul-Finebaum-ends-sybdicated-column|title=FINE-GONE: Paul Finebaum ends syndicated column|last=Carter|first=Robert|newspaper=[[The North Jefferson News]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120905225926/http://www.njeffersonnews.com/localsports/x2104923466/FINE-GONE-Paul-Finebaum-ends-sybdicated-column|archivedate=September 5, 2012}}</ref> On September 1, Finebaum returned to writing with his first column for Sports Illustrated. His weekly column appears every Thursday at SI.com.\n\n==Radio career==\n===Early career===\nFinebaum started his radio appearances in the mid-1980s by giving morning commentary on the Mark and Brian Radio Show on [[WJOX-FM|WAPI-FM (I-95)]]. After starting his own afternoon radio show a few years later on [[WAPI-AM]], his program quickly became the highest-rated sport-talk show in Birmingham. In October 1993, Finebaum moved his [[Sports radio|sports-talk show]] to [[WERC (AM)|WERC]].\n\n===The Paul Finebaum Radio Network===\nIn 2001, Finebaum, along with Network Director Pat Smith and Producer Kerry Adams, launched ''The Paul Finebaum Radio Network,'' syndicated with affiliates across the southeast. It was named in 2004 by ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' as one of the top 12 sports radio shows in the United States. In January 2007, his radio show moved to [[WJOX-FM|WJOX]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.decaturdaily.com/decaturdaily/sports/070120/radio.shtml|title=Finebaum joins WJOX radio station|publisher=[[The Decatur Daily]] (via [[Associated Press]])|date=January 20, 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20070521234552/http://www.decaturdaily.com/decaturdaily/sports/070120/radio.shtml|archivedate=May 21, 2007}}</ref>\n\nFinebaum found himself embroiled at the center of one of biggest college sports stories in America in 2011 \u2013 the poisoning of the famous trees on [[Auburn Tigers#Toomer's Corner|Toomer's Corner]] at [[Auburn University]]. The man charged, Harvey Updyke, called the Finebaum show, claiming to have poisoned the trees. The audio of the call was played on nearly every national radio show and television newscast in the nation. In the aftermath, Finebaum was featured on the ''[[NBC Nightly News|NBC Nightly News with Brian Williams]]'', appeared on CNN, ESPN, MSNBC, and several other networks. He also was blamed by many for the event including one caller saying \"if anything else happens, there will be blood on your hands.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2011/02/finebaum_catching_flak_blame_f.html|title=Is Finebaum to blame for Auburn tree poisoning? Will controversy help or hurt him?|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref> On April 21, Updyke appeared again on the Finebaum show, speaking publicly for the first time since the incident, breaking his long silence. The interview, perhaps the most listened to ever in the history of the Finebaum show, made national news, appearing in publications ranging from ''[[The New York Times]]'' to ESPN's ''[[SportsCenter]]''. Updyke ended the 45-minute interview with his signature ''Roll Damn Tide.''\n\n===ESPN===\nFinebaum's show went off the air on WJOX temporarily on January 21, 2013, when his contract with Cumulus and WJOX expired. The New Yorker reported he \"had talks with ESPN and CBS, about joining their national radio networks, and with SiriusXM, about moving permanently to satellite.\"<ref name=\"newyorker\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.newyorker.com/reporting/2012/12/10/121210fa_fact_wiedeman|magazine=[[The New Yorker]]|date=December 10, 2012|author=Wideman, Reeves|title=King of the South: How Paul Finebaum became Alabama\u2019s biggest booster}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, Finebaum signed with ESPN to appear on its new SEC Network beginning in 2014, and also host a daily radio show based out of Charlotte.<ref name=NYTimes>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/22/sports/ncaafootball/paul-finebaum-joins-espn.html|title=Radio Host Paul Finebaum joins ESPN|last=Bishop|first=Greg|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=May 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\nFinebaum's television contributions have been numerous. In Birmingham he currently{{When|date=November 2019}} appears as a sports analyst for [[WBRC]]. He was sports director for [[WIAT-TV]] from 1998 to 2002 and co-hosted individual shows on [[WVTM-TV]] and [[WBMA-LD|WBMA]].\n\nFinebaum also had a leading role in ESPN's documentary ''Roll Tide/War Eagle''. The producers used Finebaum and his program as the voice of the documentary, which debuted on November 8, 2011.\n\nAs part of the deal Finebaum signed with ESPN in May 2013, he agreed to appear on its new [[SEC Network]] starting in 2014, hosting ''The Paul Finebaum Show'' in simulcast for ESPN Radio.<ref name=NYTimes /> As an extension of the radio show, Finebaum has also hosted special broadcasts on SEC Network as part of [[ESPN Megacast]]s involving SEC teams\u2014the ''Finebaum Film Room''\u2014particularly during [[College Football Playoff National Championship]] games.<ref name=al-finebaumtrainwreck>{{cite web|title=Paul Finebaum hears 'train wreck' predictions for live Iron Bowl show, phones ready this time|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2014/11/paul_finebaum_iron_bowl_2014_live.html|website=AL.com|accessdate=30 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nFinebaum's books include his popular ''I Hate...'' series, including ''I Hate Michigan: 303 Reasons Why You Should, Too,'' and several dozen similarly titled works.\n\nFinebaum's other books include ''The Worst of Paul Finebaum'' ({{ISBN|1881548120}}), a 1994 compilation of some of the newspaper columns he has written; and ''Finebaum Said'' ({{ISBN|1931656037}}), a 2001 collection of columns and interviews.\n\nOn March 27, 2013, the Birmingham News reported that Finebaum agreed to an advance (later reported to be $650,000) with [[HarperCollins]] to write a book about the radio show. HarperCollins Senior Vice President and Executive Editor David Hirshey said \"We expect this book to occupy the same spot on the best-seller list that Alabama occupies in the BCS rankings \u2013 number one.\" In February, Publishers Weekly reported the book would arrive on August 5 with a first run of 150,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2013/03/paul_finebaum_agrees_to_book_d.html|title=Paul Finebaum agrees to book deal with HarperCollins for memoir about his radio show|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thestate.com/2013/10/05/3021379/paul-finebaum-can-talk-will-travel.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=October 13, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131014172610/http://www.thestate.com/2013/10/05/3021379/paul-finebaum-can-talk-will-travel.html |archivedate=October 14, 2013 }}</ref> The book, which was excerpted in the ''Wall Street Journal'' on August 5, quickly made the ''New York Times'' best-seller list, landing at No. 6 among sports books. The book remained on the best-seller list for five months.\n\n==Recognition==\n[[File:Paul Finebaum Jan 2018 2.jpg|thumb|Finebaum (left) at the [[2018 College Football Playoff National Championship]] media day]]\nIn 2002, Finebaum was named by ''[[The Tennessean]]'' in Nashville as one of the [[Southeastern Conference]]'s Top Power Brokers. In July 2009, ''[[The Orlando Sentinel]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/college/orl-sportspowerbox10071009jul10,0,6725131.story|title=The SEC's 10 most powerful people|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref> named Finebaum as one of the SEC's 10 most powerful people. On January 11, 2011, [[CNBC]]'s Emmy-Award-winning sports reporter, [[Darren Rovell]] wrote: \"Back 2 back titles by Alabama & Auburn make Finebaum the most powerful small market sports media member in the nation\" and called him \"the best listener of any sports talk radio host.\" In December 2012, [[Sports Illustrated]], in its year-end review of sports media, listed gave Finebaum an Honorable Mention along with 10 other names for \"Best National Radio Voice\".<ref>{{cite news| url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/more/news/media-awards-2012/ | publisher=CNN | title=SI.com's Media Awards: Best, worst from 2012 | date=December 19, 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Reeves Wiedeman]] profiled the radio host in a 5,000-word article, \"King of the South\", in the December 10, 2012 edition of ''[[the New Yorker]]''. According to the Wiedeman, it was The New Yorker's first major piece on a college football figure in more than 10 years.<ref name=\"newyorker\" /> Several months later, on February 6, 2013, The ''[[Wall Street Journal]]'', in a profile by writer [[Rachel Bachman]], stated: \"Paul Finebaum is not only one of the nation's best-known sports-talk radio hosts. He is perhaps college football's best-known voice since TV announcer [[Keith Jackson]] retired.\" The Journal ended the story, referring to Finebaum as \"the [[Oprah Winfrey]] of college football.\" On March 6, 2013, ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''{{'}}s Richard Deitsch unveiled a ranking of the 20 Most Powerful People in Sports Media nationally and Finebaum came in at No. 17.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/more/news/20130306/most-powerful-people-sports-media/ | publisher=CNN | title=Ranking the 10 most powerful people in sports media | date=March 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, ''The Big Lead'', part of USA Today's sports online network, ranked Finebaum No. 18 in a piece on ''The 25 Most Powerful People in Sports Media'', writing: \"He was profiled by the New Yorker, and that was before he became a multimedia presence on ESPN and the SEC Network. His radio show is a focal point for college football fans and media members. He can alter the sport's national discussion with an interview, a hot bit of gossip, and offhand comment or a tweet.\" {{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\nIn July 2015, the college football website, ''Saturday Down South'', ranked Finebaum No. 3 among the SEC's most influential people, saying \"Finebaum has masterfully positioned himself to be \"the voice of the SEC.\"{{Cn|date=November 2019}} At the conclusion of SEC Media Days, \"Saturday Down South\" also ranked the top 10 commentators and media figures, and Finebaum was ranked No. 1. \"There was really little question as to who would top this list,\" wrote Saturday Down South. \"In the midst of facilitating what can turn into a crazy sideshow, Finebaum has managed to develop one of the league's most respected voices.\"{{Cn|date=November 2019}}\n\nIn January 2017, The Big Lead had Finebaum No. 25 on a list of ''The 30 Most Powerful Talents in Sports Media Today'', saying: \"Finebaum owns the SEC region, and when he wields his cudgel on a coach or program in scandal, it cuts deeper than just about any voice. He has his finger on the pulse of Nick Saban and Alabama, which you might as well write in the CFB playoffs every year in a Sharpie.\" On February 1, 2018 Jason Barrett of Barrett Sports Media, polled 35 radio executives from the nation, and listed Finebaum No. 7 in \"America's Top 20 National Sports Shows of 2017.\"{{citation needed|date=December 2018}} In January 2019, The Big Lead ranked the 75 Most Powerful People in the Sports Media, a list ranging from Disney chairman Bob Iger and Fox chief Rupert Murdoch to LeBron James to sports talent on various network. Finebaum came in at No. 35, tied with Jay Bilas. ``Paul Finebaum and Jay Bilas are arguably the most influential voices on college football and college basketball respectively. Finebaum has a huge impact on the most important region in the sport ... They (Finebaum and Bilas) are two truly untouchable voices.\" In February 2019, Jason Barrett's annual ranking of the Top 20 National Sports Shows saw Finebaum land at No. 6. In July 2019, Buddy Martin, a respected journalist, and now editor of GatorBait Magazine, conducted a poll at SEC Media Days among media members and found Finebaum to be the most influential member of the SEC media, and it was nearly unanimous. ``Nobody else was even close,'' Martin wrote. Alan Blinder, who covers college football for the New York Times, voted three times. 1. Paul Finebaum, 2. Paul Finebaum and 3. Paul Finebaum. Mike Bianchi of the Orlando Sentinel was even stronger:``Paul Finebaum is not only the 'Most Influential' member here - he's the `Most Influential' in all of college football.''\n\nIn October 2013, the University of Tennessee presenting Finebaum with the \"Accomplished Alumni Award,\" \"which recognizes notable alumni for their success and distinction within their field.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utk.edu/tntoday/2013/10/18/renowned-sports-journalist-honored-accomplished-alumni-award|title=Renowned Sports Journalist Honored with Accomplished Alumni Award|date=October 18, 2013|accessdate=October 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn June 23, 2016, Finebaum delivered the keynote at the annual meeting of the Associated Press Sports Editors annual convention in Charlotte. He gave an emotionally charged address, challenging the group to remain firm to its core principals, adding \"journalism is not a reality show.\" A copy of the speech is available at apsportseditors.org.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} In May 2018, Finebaum delivered the eulogy of his close friend SEC Commissioner Mike Slive in Birmingham, an occasion live-streamed on Al.com. Kevin Scarbinsky, the long-time columnist, said: ''His eulogy for dear friend Mike Slive had to be among the most personal and painful minutes Finebaum ever spent behind a microphone. Paul's moving tribute may have been his finest hour.''{{Cn|date=November 2019}}\n\n==Personal life==\nFinebaum was born in Memphis, Tennessee.  He and his wife Linda Hudson have been married since 1990.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.annistonstar.com/sports/once-a-birmingham-sports-columnist-finebaum-hits-the-big-time/article_b52c9876-4ec5-11e5-9d7c-1f7024629a1c.html|title=Once a Birmingham sports columnist, Finebaum hits the big time at ESPN|date=August 23, 2015|last=Hester|first=Wayne|newspaper=[[The Anniston Star]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006050950/http://www.annistonstar.com/sports/once-a-birmingham-sports-columnist-finebaum-hits-the-big-time/article_b52c9876-4ec5-11e5-9d7c-1f7024629a1c.html|archivedate=October 26, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Finebaum is [[Jewish]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url= http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2012/12/10/king-of-the-south|title= King of the South|date=December 10, 2012|last=Wiedman|first=Reeves|magazine=[[The New Yorker]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espn.com/espn/page2/story?id=1907341 |title=Rammer Jammer Yellow Hammer |last=St. John |first=Warren |date=December 10, 2012 |access-date=October 2, 2019 |publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/podcasts/hang_up_and_listen/2012/12/paul_finebaum_alabama_hang_up_and_listen_on_the_jovan_belcher_murder_suicide.html|title=Hang Up and Listen: The How To Talk About a Murder-Suicide Edition. Slate\u2019s sports podcast on Jovan Belcher, Alabama sports radio host Paul Finebaum, and the contretemps over the Spurs resting their starters.|date=December 3, 2012|last1=Fatsis|first1=Stefan|last2=Levin|first2=Josh|last3=Pesca|first3=Mike|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* Barnes, Susan. (Summer 2005) \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20060507224422/http://pr.tennessee.edu/alumnus/alumarticle.asp?id=628 The Devil We Know]\". ''Tennessee Alumnus Magazine''. Vol. 85, No. 3 \u2013 accessed April 16, 2006\n* Paul Finebaum is \"the most influential sports-talk personality in the Southeast\" \u2013 Huntsville Times, August 21, 2003.\n* \"Paul Finebaum, the state's most influential sports columnist and talk-show host\" \u2013 New York Times, May 4, 2003.\n* Fowler, Jeremy. \"Finebaum voted as one of the SEC's 10 most powerful people\"- \"[http://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/college/orl-sportspowerbox10071009jul10,0,6725131.story ]\". Orlando Sentinel, July 10, 2009.\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.facebook.com/PaulFinebaum Paul Finebaum Official Facebook Page]\n*[http://www.finebaum.com Paul Finebaum Radio Network official site]\n*[http://www.al.com/sports/birminghamnews/index.ssf?/base/sports/116921267611600.xml&coll=2 Finebaum headed to WJOX, ''Birmingham News'']\n*[http://www.cranehill.com/ihate.html Cranehill Press \"I Hate...\" Series]\n* [http://www.bhamwiki.com/wiki/index.php?title=Paul_Finebaum Paul Finebaum] article at BhamWiki.com\n*[http://www.radiojunkee.com Listen to Paul Finebaum Show on RadioJunkee.com]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Finebaum, Paul}}\n[[Category:American columnists]]\n[[Category:American sportswriters]]\n[[Category:American sports radio personalities]]\n[[Category:American television personalities]]\n[[Category:Writers from Birmingham, Alabama]]\n[[Category:People from Memphis, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Tennessee alumni]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Alabama]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Jewish American sportspeople]]\n", "name_user": "Lebron2", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Finebaum"}
